  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: cf5142e3d00304443bc2d9e5770d15df, type: 3}
  m_Name: RainforestQuiz
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::QuizData
  quizTitle: Zara's Quest
  passingScore: 3
  questions:
  - questionText: 'Rainforests cover only 6% of Earth''s surface but

      contain
      what percentage of all plant and animal species?'
    answers:
    - Around 10%
    - Around 25%
    - Over 50%
    - Around 5%
    correctAnswerIndex: 2
    wrongFeedback: Tropical rainforests contain over 50% of the world's plant and
      animal species despite covering just 6% of the surface. A single hectare can
      contain more tree species than all of Northern Europe combined. This density
      of life is exactly why deforestation is so catastrophic, destroying a small
      area wipes out enormous biodiversity irreversibly.
    correctFeedback: Well done!
  - questionText: What is the main reason companies clear rainforest in Southeast
      Asia specifically?
    answers:
    - To build roads and cities
    - To create palm oil plantations
    - To mine for gold and copper
    - To grow rice and wheat
    correctAnswerIndex: 1
    wrongFeedback: Palm oil is the leading driver of deforestation in Indonesia and
      Malaysia, which together produce 85% of the world's supply. It is found in
      roughly half of all supermarket products under hundreds of different ingredient
      names. Forests are often cleared by burning, which releases massive stored
      carbon directly into the atmosphere and destroys habitat that took thousands
      of years to form.
    correctFeedback: Well done!
  - questionText: Zara loses her poison if she leaves the rainforest. What does this
      tell us about ecosystems?
    answers:
    - Poison is a learned behaviour, not biological
    - Frogs are not actually toxic, it is a myth
    - 'Species are deeply dependent on specific   conditions and organisms within
      their habitat '
    - Toxicity increases outside of rainforests
    correctAnswerIndex: 2
    wrongFeedback: Poison dart frogs get their toxicity from eating specific rainforest
      insects which themselves feed on specific plants. Remove any link in that chain
      and the whole thing collapses. This is called trophic dependency and it applies
      to almost every species on Earth. It is why habitat destruction is more dangerous
      than it first appears, you are not just removing trees, you are dismantling
      an entire interdependent system.
    correctFeedback: Well done!
  - questionText: When a rainforest is burned or cleared, it stops absorbing carbon
      and starts releasing it. What is this called?
    answers:
    - Carbon flooding
    - Atmospheric reversal
    - Tipping point collapse
    - Carbon source flip
    correctAnswerIndex: 3
    wrongFeedback: A forest that absorbs more carbon than it releases is called a
      carbon sink. When it is destroyed it becomes a carbon source, releasing centuries
      of stored carbon all at once. The Amazon is already beginning this flip in
      its eastern regions due to drought and deforestation. Scientists call this
      dieback. If it reaches a tipping point the process becomes self-sustaining
      and irreversible, releasing an estimated 90 billion tons of carbon.
    correctFeedback: Well done!
